The Kubernetes Crusade: Workshop on Defending & Attacking Kubernetes

Lab: Docker Layers & Dockerfile Demo

Building httpd docker container via dockerfile running on port 80

Open New Terminal (Optional)

If current working directory is not workspace/course

  • Click on + icon, then select new terminal to open new terminal.

  • Keep current working directory as workspace/course
cd course/

Hands On

  • Navigate to the course/docker_layers/ directory by running the command cd course/docker_layers/.
cd 3.3_docker_layers/
  • Use the command docker images to view the list of currently available images.
docker images
  • Verify the output of the docker images command.

  • To examine the contents of the Dockerfile, run the command cat Dockerfile.
cat Dockerfile
  • Verify the output of the cat Dockerfile command and examine the contents.

  • Build the Docker image from the Dockerfile by running the command docker build -t my-httpd-image ..
docker build -t my-httpd-image .
  • Verify the output of the docker build command and examine the contents:

  • Analyze the layers of the Docker image by running the command docker history "my-httpd-image".
docker history my-httpd-image
  • Verify the output of the docker history command.

  • Use the command "docker images" to view the list of available images again.
docker images
  • Check the images present locally, including the newly built my-httpd-image and the base image httpd.

  • Run a Docker container using my-httpd-image by executing the command docker run -d -p 8081:80 --name my-httpd-container my-httpd-image.
docker run -d -p 8081:80 --name my-httpd-container my-httpd-image
  • Verify that the container has been successfully built and obtains the container ID.

  • Retrieve the public IP of the running EC2 instance by running the command curl http://checkip.amazonaws.com.
echo $(curl -s http://checkip.amazonaws.com):8081

  • Use the public IP to access the container running on port 80.

  • Open a new tab in the browser and enter the public IP address to access the container.

Cleanup:

  • Stop the container by running the command docker stop my-httpd-container.
docker stop my-httpd-container
  • Verify that the container has been successfully stopped.

  • Remove the container by running the command docker rm my-httpd-container.
docker rm my-httpd-container
  • Verify that the container has been successfully removed by examining the contents.

  • Remove the my-httpd-image by running the command docker rmi my-httpd-image.
docker rmi my-httpd-image
  • Verify that the image has been successfully removed.

  • Remove the base image httpd by running the command docker rmi httpd.
docker rmi httpd
  • Verify that the base image has been successfully removed.

  • Check all the images have been deleted by running the command `docker images, which should return an empty list.
docker images
  • Blank output shows no images are present:

Basics of Layers

  • Docker containers are building blocks for applications. Each container is an image with a readable/writeable layer on top of a bunch of read-only layers.

  • These layers, also called intermediate images are generated when the commands in the Dockerfile are executed during the Docker image build.

Exploring images:

  • There are a few tools that allows you to explore container images like Dive, in the next section let's perform the analysis of docker layers using Dive.
